		<header>
			
			<h1>FAO/IFAD publication sets out potential route to greater food security in West Africa </h1>

			
			<h4>
												02 March 2014
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>A joint FAO/IFAD publication entitled ‘Rebuilding West Africa’s food potential: Policies and market incentives for smallholder-inclusive food value chains’ has been published, bringing together seven analytical policy pieces and nine case studies on the scope for development and the agricultural potential of West Africa. Products covered include: cocoa, cotton, high-value horticulture products, palm oil, rice, sorghum, millet and cassava. </p><p>The publication calls on West African governments to “direct greater efforts to develop… staple food crops, which in the past have been sidelined in favour of a few export commodities”. It maintains that “maize and cassava… could form the backbone for a thriving agro-industry given their multiple market applications,” while rice production offers huge potential, in view of the deficit in production in West Africa (70% of the region’s rice consumption is imported). In addition, the publication maintains that “yields on sorghum and millet… could double or triple with the help of improved seed varieties.” </p><p>However, it is recognised that there is little incentive for farmers “to increase production if they can’t sell their crops because of cheaper and easily accessible imports”. It is against this background that it is argued that “policy and market incentives are needed to improve the competitiveness of locally grown crops and increase their share in the consumer market.” </p><p>While calling for a greater policy focus on staple crops, this FAO publication “underscores the importance of continued investment in export crops such as cotton, coffee and cocoa, which play a significant role in generating income and employment”, and highlights the potential for growth in tropical fruit and vegetable exports targeting emerging niche markets. </p><p>The publication further argues for the “tapping [of] unexploited trade potential… within the region”, which is seen as “critical for agricultural development”. According to the editor, “the real challenge for West Africa is learning how to unlock the intraregional trade potential”, by addressing key constraints such as “poor transport networks, excessive regulation and conflicting trade policies among different countries, all of which result in costly delays on West African trade routes”. </p><p>The publication further calls for greater attention to be paid to public–private sector partnerships “to improve access to credit and markets for small-scale farmers”, particularly for women farmers. This is seen as vital to strengthening “post-harvest processing and marketing”. Closely linked to this, the publication highlights “the importance of strengthening farmers’ organizations”, particularly strengthening their capacity “to negotiate arrangements with suppliers and buyers” and play a full role in policy dialogue with governments.&nbsp;</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>FAO, ‘West Africa has potential to strengthen its agricultural sector’, 18 December 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://www.fao.org/news/story/en/item/202048/icode/" target="_self">http://www.fao.org/news/story/en/item/202048/icode/</a>&nbsp;</p><p>FAO/IFAD, ‘Rebuilding West Africa’s food potential: Policies and market incentives for smallholder-inclusive food value chains’, 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://www.fao.org/docrep/018/i3222e/i3222e.pdf" target="_self">http://www.fao.org/docrep/018/i3222e/i3222e.pdf</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>At the policy level, a critical regional challenge in West Africa is building a consensus on what “policy and market incentives” are needed and appropriate for the successful stimulation of domestic production of staple food crops. At the national level, the challenge is then to design and implement such appropriate policy and market incentives. </p><p>Currently, West African governments have in place different policy frameworks making use of different policy tools, which have different market effects. While most national governments have identified similar priority commodities in their national agricultural investment plans, a lack of operational harmonisation at the regional level creates challenges for the development of regional commodity supply chains. This is despite the existence of a Regional Agricultural Investment Plan.</p><p>Beyond the need for greater policy coordination/harmonisation, increased operational cooperation in the development of trade-related infrastructure – both ‘soft’ infrastructure and the ‘hard’ infrastructure – would be likely to prove more cost-effective if pursued at the regional level. </p><p>ECOWAS member states have agreed on a multiplicity of initiatives at the regional level aimed at improving both the ‘soft’ and ‘hard’ infrastructure required to facilitate agricultural trade. However, to date progress in implementation varies considerably between member states, with overall progress sometimes seen as slow, despite a range of promising area-specific initiatives. </p><p>Creating reliable, profitable regional markets for expanded national production thus remains a challenge, particularly given the need to reconcile the interests of producers and consumers and the divergent approaches to agricultural trade policy that characterise the region. </p><p>As the FAO/IFAD publication highlights, getting to grips with this challenge is central to any effective take-up of agronomic improvements designed to boost regional food production.</p>
		</div>
		
